# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alesia-city
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alesia-city/abrincatui] The **Abrincatui** or **Abricantui** were a Gallic tribe dwelling in the south of the Cotentin Peninsula during the Roman period.
[src:alesia-city/abrincatui] They are mentioned as *Abrincatuos* by Pliny (1st c.
[src:alesia-city/abrincatui] AD), *’Abrinkátouoi* (’Aβρινκάτουοι) by Ptolemy (2nd c.
[src:alesia-city/abrincatui] AD), and as *Abrincatis* and *Abrincateni* in the *Notitia Dignitatum* (5th c.
[src:alesia-city/abrincatui] The city of Avranches, attested in the 6th c.
[src:alesia-city/abrincatui] AD as *civitas* *Abrincatum* ('civitas of the Abrincatui', *Abrincae* ca.
[src:alesia-city/abrincatui] 550, *de Avrenchis* in 1055–66), and the region of Avranchin, are named after the Gallic tribe.
[src:alesia-city/abrincatui] The territory of the Abrincatui mostly corresponded the later regions of Avranchin and Mortainais.
[src:alesia-city/abrincatui] It was inherited with only slight border changes by the *civitas* *Abrincatum* and, later, by the diocese of Avranches.
[src:alesia-city/abrincatui] However, the area of Mortainais was mostly uninhabited until the Roman period, and remained sparsely populated at the turn of the first millennium AD.
[src:alesia-city/abrincatui] Two pre-Roman oppida were located in Le Petit-Celland and Carolles, with other settlements in Montanel and near Mortain.
[src:alesia-city/abrincatui] They were a client tribe of the Venelli until the Roman occupation in 49 BC, when they were separated.
[src:alesia-city/acitavones] The **Acitavones** were a small Gallic tribe dwelling in the Alps during the Iron Age.
[src:alesia-city/acitavones] They are mentioned as *Acitavones* (var.
[src:alesia-city/acitavones] The etymology of the name *Acitauones* is unclear.
[src:alesia-city/acitavones] The first element, *acito*-, could mean 'field' (cf.
[src:alesia-city/acitavones] Old Irish *ached*, *achad*)*,* or else be a variant of *agido*- ('face, appearance').
[src:alesia-city/acitavones] According to historian Guy Barruol, they may have dwelled in the Aosta Valley, near the Little St Bernard Pass.
[src:alesia-city/acitavones] The *Barrington Atlas* locates their territory north of the Medulli and Segusini, south of the Veragri, west of the Salassi, and east of the Ceutrones.
[src:alesia-city/acitavones] They are mentioned by Pliny the Elder as one of the Alpine tribes conquered by Rome in 16–15 BC, and whose name was engraved on the Tropaeum Alpium.
[src:alesia-city/adanates] The **Adanates** or **Edenates** were a small Gallic tribe dwelling around present-day Seyne, in the Alpes Cottiae, during the Iron Age.
[src:alesia-city/adanates] AD), and as *Adanatium* on the Arc of Susa.
[src:alesia-city/adanates] The etymology of the name *Adanates* is unclear.
[src:alesia-city/adanates] Guy Barruol has proposed to compare it with *Adenatius* (or *Adenatis*) and *Adana*, and postulated an original **Senedenates*, with loss of the initial *s-* retained in *Sedena*, the name of their chief town.
[src:alesia-city/adanates] According to Alexander Falileyev, "if the original form was indeed **Sed-*, the name could be Celtic, from *sedo-* 'seat, location'; but in view of the form recorded in inscriptions, it is unlikely.
[src:alesia-city/adanates] If *Eden-* is the original form, the name does not appear Celtic." Xavier Delamarre has proposed to interpret the name as *Ed-en-ati* ('those from the land/country'), from a Gaulish stem *edo-(n)-* ('space, land').
[src:alesia-city/adanates] The Adanates dwelled around the settlement of Sedena (modern Seyne).
[src:alesia-city/adanates] The *Barrington Atlas* locates their territory south of the Avantici, west of the Savincates, east of the Sebaginni, and north of the Gallitae and Eguiturii.
[src:alesia-city/adanates] They also appear on the Arch of Susa, erected by Cottius in 9–8 BC.
[src:alesia-city/adunicates] The **Adunicates** were a small Gallic tribe dwelling in the upper Durance valley during the Roman era.
[src:alesia-city/adunicates] They are mentioned as *Adunicates* by Pliny (1st c.
[src:alesia-city/adunicates] If Celtic, it may be interpreted as a haplology (loss of syllable) of Gaulish **Andedunicates*, based on the intensifying prefix *ande*-.
[src:alesia-city/adunicates] In this view, it could be compared to the personal names *Andedunis* and *Atedunus* ('big fort').
[src:alesia-city/adunicates] The Adunicates lived in the upper Durance valley.
[src:alesia-city/adunicates] They are mentioned by Pliny as living near the Suetrii and the Quariates, north of the Oxybii and Ligauni.
[src:alesia-city/aedui] The **Aedui** or **Haedui** (Gaulish: **Aiduoi*, 'the Ardent') were a Gallic people dwelling in central-eastern Gaul, in the country between the Loire and the Saône (modern Burgundy), during the Iron Age and the Roman period.
[src:alesia-city/aedui] From the middle of the 2nd century BC they were allies of Rome, the first people of inner Gaul to conclude a formal treaty (*foedus*) with the Republic and, according to Tacitus, the only Gauls to bear the title *fratres populi Romani* ('brothers of the Roman people').
[src:alesia-city/aedui] During the Gallic Wars (58–50 BC) they gave Caesar important if uneven support before briefly joining the revolt of Vercingetorix in 52 BC.
[src:alesia-city/aedui] Their aristocracy was thereafter rapidly integrated into the Roman order, and under Claudius in 48 AD they were the first Gauls admitted to the Roman Senate.
[src:alesia-city/aedui] Their principal *oppidum*, Bibracte on Mont Beuvray, was replaced under Augustus by a new capital, Augustodunum (Autun).
[src:alesia-city/aedui] They are mentioned as *Haedui* by Cicero (mid-1st c.
[src:alesia-city/aedui] AD), *Aidúōn* (Αἰδύων) by Ptolemy (2nd c.
[src:alesia-city/aedui] AD), and as *Aídouoi* (Aἴδουοι) by Cassius Dio (3rd c.
[src:alesia-city/aedui] The ethnonym *Aedui* is a Latinized form of Gaulish **Aiduoi* (sing.
[src:alesia-city/aedui] It derives from the Celtic stem **aidu-* ('fire, ardour', cf.
[src:alesia-city/aedui] Old Irish *áed* 'fire', Welsh *aidd* 'ardour'), itself from Proto-Indo-European: **h₂eydʰos* ('firewood', cf.
[src:alesia-city/aedui] Sanskrit *édhas* 'bonfire', Latin *aedes* 'building, temple').
[src:alesia-city/aedui] The Aedui held a central position in eastern Gaul, on the watershed dividing the Mediterranean, Atlantic and Channel drainage basins.
[src:alesia-city/aedui] Their territory was bounded on the west by the Loire (*Liger*), which separated them from the Bituriges, and on the east by the Saône (*Arar*), which separated them from the Sequani.
[src:alesia-city/aedui] To the south lay their clients the Segusiavi and the first foothills of the Massif Central, held by the Arverni, and to the north the edge of the Morvan and the country of their clients the Mandubii.
[src:alesia-city/aedui] The river ports of *Cabillonum* (Chalon-sur-Saône) and *Matisco* (Mâcon) controlled the traffic of the Saône.
[src:alesia-city/aedui] The Saône did not, however, form a stable linear frontier.
[src:alesia-city/aedui] The river was easily forded and presented no real obstacle.
[src:alesia-city/aedui] The boundary between Aedui and Sequani was sinuous rather than parallel to its course, with Aeduan enclaves on the eastern bank (notably around Chalon and Verdun) and Sequanian holdings to the west.
[src:alesia-city/aedui] A weakly occupied zone south of Chalon, on the Bresse side, seems to have formed a kind of march separating the two peoples.
[src:alesia-city/aedui] Three oppida are known from the end of the La Tène period: Vieux-Dun (Dun-les-Places), Le Fou de Verdun (Lavault-de-Frétoy), and Bibracte, which occupied a central position in the Aedian economic system.
[src:alesia-city/aedui] Bibracte, the principal *oppidum* of the Aedui, occupied an isolated hill of the Morvan (Mont Beuvray, culminating at 820 m) at the meeting point of the basins of the Yonne, the Loire, the Seine and the Saône.
[src:alesia-city/aedui] Occupied and probably fortified since the Neolithic, it reached its height in the 1st century BC before being progressively abandoned towards the end of that century in favour of Augustodunum.
[src:alesia-city/aedui] The interior was hierarchically arranged, with sanctuaries on the highest points, aristocratic residences and the market on the plateau.
[src:alesia-city/aedui] The craft quarters were located lower down, near the gates and in the outer suburb between the two lines of rampart.
[src:alesia-city/aedui] Augustodunum's earliest urban occupation barely predates the turn of the era.
[src:alesia-city/aedui] Only a small and unevenly distributed part of the urban area, of the order of one per cent, has been excavated down to the earliest levels as of 2015, so that the picture of the Julio-Claudian town remains very incomplete.
[src:alesia-city/aedui] Before the Roman conquest the Aedui were one of the major political and military powers of central Gaul, contending for a preeminence with their powerful neighbours, the Sequani, Bituriges and Arverni.
[src:alesia-city/aedui] Their *civitas* was an oligarchy in which the conduct of affairs lay with a senate, an assembly probably made up of the representatives of the great families, which had replaced the older assembly of the people in arms, convened only in exceptional cases such as a declaration of war.
[src:alesia-city/aedui] Current business and the administration of justice lay with an annual magistrate, the *vergobret*, elected for one year, probably by the senate.
[src:alesia-city/aedui] The names of several holders are known: Dumnorix (ca.
[src:alesia-city/aedui] 60 BC), Liscos (58 BC), Valetiacos (53 BC), and Cotos, whose contested election in 52 BC was settled by Caesar in favour of his rival Convictolitavis.
[src:alesia-city/aedui] A law forbade the supreme magistrate to leave the territory of the *civitas*.
[src:alesia-city/aedui] The farming of taxes and tolls was let by auction.
[src:alesia-city/aedui] The Aedui concluded an alliance with Rome at an undetermined moment around 150–140 BC.
[src:alesia-city/aedui] With the Remi they were the traditional allies of Rome in Gaul, and according to Livy they were already allied with the Republic before 121 BC, when Domitius Ahenobarbus invoked the alliance in order to campaign against the Allobroges.
[src:alesia-city/aedui] They were the first people of inner Gaul to contract such an alliance and, according to Tacitus, the only Gauls to bear the title *fratres populi Romani*.
[src:alesia-city/aedui] This title was granted at the moment the *foedus* was concluded and reconfirmed by successive decrees of the Senate.
[src:alesia-city/aedui] The treaty was a *foedus aequum*, an equal treaty resting on reciprocal *fides* between two peoples whose territories were not contiguous.
[src:alesia-city/aedui] It entailed mutual military assistance together with the right of hospitality (*hospitalitas*).
[src:alesia-city/aedui] Caesar called the Aedui consanguineous brothers (*fratres consanguinei*).
[src:alesia-city/aedui] The alliance brought lasting Roman influence, as shown by a silver coinage aligned on the denarius and the early introduction of Roman-style architecture at Bibracte, a site that Olivier Buchsenschutz has described as a bridgehead of Roman influence towards the north of Gaul.
[src:alesia-city/aedui] In 61 BC the Aeduan noble Diviciacus appealed to the Roman Senate for help against the Sequani, Arverni and Germani, but in vain.
[src:alesia-city/aedui] Diviciacus, brother of Dumnorix and a partisan of Rome, had been received at Rome by Cicero, who records that he was a Druid.
[src:alesia-city/aedui] He became Caesar's trusted intermediary.
[src:alesia-city/aedui] When the Helvetii resolved to migrate to the country of the Santones across Aeduan territory, the *foedus* served Caesar as a pretext to intervene in the still unconquered part of Gauls (*Gallia comata*).
[src:alesia-city/aedui] At the Aedui's request Caesar intervened in 58 BC against the Germani of Ariovistus, then allied with the Sequani within an Arvernian coalition.
[src:alesia-city/aedui] Diviciacus guided the Roman legions into Alsace for the decisive battle.
[src:alesia-city/aedui] His brother Dumnorix led the anti-Roman faction.
[src:alesia-city/aedui] As son-in-law of the Helvetian Orgetorix, he had held the supreme magistracy shortly before 58 BC and had farmed the Aeduan tolls and taxes for several consecutive years.
[src:alesia-city/aedui] His wealth allowed him to maintain a body of cavalry as a personal guard, and he commanded the Aeduan cavalry furnished to Caesar.
[src:alesia-city/aedui] His collusion with the Helvetii was treated as treason, and he was spared only through his brother's influence.
[src:alesia-city/aedui] In 54 BC, at *Portus Itius* (Boulogne), he refused to embark for Britain and was killed in flight, crying that he was a free man belonging to a free people.
[src:alesia-city/aedui] During the war the Aedui were divided, supporting the Romans most of the time but also the insurgents during the brief revolt of 52 BC.
[src:alesia-city/aedui] After Caesar's final victory they kept their laws and their title of *fratres populi Romani*.
[src:alesia-city/aedui] As allies, the Aedui were not conquered but received Roman citizenship directly.
[src:alesia-city/aedui] Their capital was transferred from Bibracte to a new town, Augustodunum (Autun), created *ex nihilo* on the order of Augustus at the end of the 1st century BC.
[src:alesia-city/aedui] It lay about twenty kilometres west of Bibracte, on the road laid out under Agrippa.
[src:alesia-city/aedui] From its creation the city was enclosed by a wall some 6 kilometres long delimiting nearly 200 hectares, a privilege normally reserved for Latin or Roman colonies.
[src:alesia-city/aedui] It took the name of its founder: Augustodunum ('the town of Augustus'), from the Gaulish suffix *-dunum* ('town, fortress').
[src:alesia-city/aedui] The legal status of the city is disputed.
[src:alesia-city/aedui] Pliny lists it among the federated communities (*civitates foederatae*), but Antony Hostein, treating Pliny's testimony with caution, argues that the *civitas* held the status of a Latin-right colony from early on, perhaps from its foundation.
[src:alesia-city/aedui] Excavation suggests that the move was a gradual shift rather than a sudden abandonment: the public buildings and craft quarters were transferred first in the last decade BC.
[src:alesia-city/aedui] The aristocratic habitat moved later, only a sparse occupation remaining on the old *oppidum* after about 15 BC.
[src:alesia-city/aedui] Under Claudius, a delegation of Gallic notables (the *primores Galliae*, designated by the council of the Ara Romae at Lyon) petitioned the emperor and the Senate in 48 AD for the right to pursue a senatorial career at Rome.
[src:alesia-city/aedui] Claudius supported the request, but the Senate granted access not to the notables of all Three Gauls but to the Aedui alone as old allies The Aedui thus became the first Gauls to obtain the right to sit in the Roman Senate.
[src:alesia-city/aedui] In 269–270 AD, Augustodunum was besieged for seven months and sacked.
[src:alesia-city/aedui] The city had declared for the legitimate emperor Claudius II, the Aedui being the first to solicit his help to recover the Gauls against the Gallic emperor Victorinus.
[src:alesia-city/aedui] Defended by its population, the city fell when the relief it awaited failed to arrive.
[src:alesia-city/aedui] The repression that followed included the proscription of the city's notables and the confiscation of their property.
[src:alesia-city/aedui] The city was restored under the Tetrarchy and Constantine, and in 312 it was renamed *Flavia Aeduorum* in honour of Constantine.
[src:alesia-city/aedui] The only Druid named among the Aedui is Diviciacus, whom Cicero received at Rome and recorded as a member of the order.
[src:alesia-city/aedui] At Augustodunum, inscriptions attest the cult of the goddess Bibracte, who bears the name of the former *oppidum*, of Anvallos, and the presence of a temple of Apollo.
[src:alesia-city/aedui] The Temple of Janus, probably erected second half of the 1st century AD, was located just outside Augustodunum.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] Platforms for aerial photography include fixed-wing aircraft, helicopters, unmanned aerial vehicles (UAVs or "drones"), balloons, blimps and dirigibles, rockets, pigeons, kites, or using action cameras while skydiving or wingsuiting.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] Handheld cameras may be manually operated by the photographer, while mounted cameras are usually remotely operated or triggered automatically.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] Aerial photography typically refers specifically to bird's-eye view images that focus on landscapes and surface objects, and should not be confused with air-to-air photography, where one or more aircraft are used as chase planes that "chase" and photograph other aircraft in flight.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] Elevated photography can also produce bird's-eye images closely resembling aerial photography (despite not actually being aerial shots) when telephotoing from high vantage structures, suspended on cables (e.g.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] Skycam) or on top of very tall poles that are either handheld (e.g. monopods and selfie sticks), fixed firmly to the ground (e.g. surveillance cameras and crane shots) or mounted above vehicles.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] Aerial photography was first practiced by the French photographer and balloonist Gaspard-Félix Tournachon, known as "Nadar", in 1858 over Paris, France.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] However, the photographs he produced no longer exist and therefore the earliest surviving aerial photograph is titled 'Boston, as the Eagle and the Wild Goose See It.' Taken by James Wallace Black and Samuel Archer King on October 13, 1860, it depicts Boston from a height of 630m.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] Kite aerial photography was pioneered by British meteorologist E.D.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] He used an explosive charge on a timer to take photographs from the air.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] The same year, Cecil Shadbolt devised a method of taking photographs from the basket of a gas balloon, including shots looking vertically downwards.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] One of his images, taken from 2,000 feet (610 m) over Stamford Hill, is the earliest extant aerial photograph taken in the British Isles.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] A print of the same image, *An Instantaneous Map Photograph taken from the Car of a Balloon, 2,000 feet high*, was shown at the 1882 Photographic Society exhibition.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] Frenchman Arthur Batut began using kites for photography in 1888, and wrote a book on his methods in 1890.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] Samuel Franklin Cody developed his advanced 'Man-lifter War Kite' and succeeded in interesting the British War Office with its capabilities.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] In 1908, Albert Samama Chikly filmed the first ever aerial views using a balloon between Hammam-Lif and Grombalia.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] The first use of a motion picture camera mounted to a heavier-than-air aircraft took place on April 24, 1909, over Rome in the 3:28 silent film short, *Wilbur Wright und seine Flugmaschine*.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] The use of aerial photography rapidly matured during the war, as reconnaissance aircraft were equipped with cameras to record enemy movements and defenses.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] At the start of the conflict, the usefulness of aerial photography was not fully appreciated, with reconnaissance being accomplished with map sketching from the air.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] Germany adopted the first aerial camera, a Görz, in 1913.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] The French began the war with several squadrons of Blériot observation aircraft equipped with cameras for reconnaissance.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] The French Army developed procedures for getting prints into the hands of field commanders in record time.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] Frederick Charles Victor Laws started aerial photography experiments in 1912 with No.1 Squadron of the Royal Flying Corps (later No.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] 1 Squadron RAF), taking photographs from the British dirigible *Beta*.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] He discovered that vertical photos taken with a 60% overlap could be used to create a stereoscopic effect when viewed in a stereoscope, thus creating a perception of depth that could aid in cartography and in intelligence derived from aerial images.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] The Royal Flying Corps recon pilots began to use cameras for recording their observations in 1914 and by the Battle of Neuve Chapelle in 1915, the entire system of German trenches was being photographed.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] In 1916, the Austro-Hungarian Monarchy made vertical camera axis aerial photos above Italy for map-making.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] The first purpose-built and practical aerial camera was invented by Captain John Moore-Brabazon in 1915 with the help of the Thornton-Pickard company, greatly enhancing the efficiency of aerial photography.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] The camera was inserted into the floor of the aircraft and could be triggered by the pilot at intervals.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] Moore-Brabazon also pioneered the incorporation of stereoscopic techniques into aerial photography, allowing the height of objects on the landscape to be discerned by comparing photographs taken at different angles.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] In January 1918, General Allenby used five Australian pilots from No.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] 1 Squadron AFC to photograph a 624 square miles (1,620 km2) area in Palestine as an aid to correcting and improving maps of the Turkish front.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] This was a pioneering use of aerial photography as an aid for cartography.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] Lieutenants Leonard Taplin, Allan Runciman Brown, H.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] Rogers photographed a block of land stretching from the Turkish front lines 32 miles (51 km) deep into their rear areas.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] Beginning 5 January, they flew with a fighter escort to ward off enemy fighters.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] Using Royal Aircraft Factory BE.12 and Martinsyde airplanes, they not only overcame enemy air attacks, but also had to contend with 65 mph (105 km/h) winds, antiaircraft fire, and malfunctioning equipment to complete their task.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] The first commercial aerial photography company in the UK was Aerofilms Ltd, founded by World War I veterans Francis Wills and Claude Graham White in 1919.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] The company soon expanded into a business with major contracts in Africa and Asia as well as in the UK.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] Operations began from the Stag Lane Aerodrome at Edgware, using the aircraft of the London Flying School.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] Subsequently, the Aircraft Manufacturing Company (later the De Havilland Aircraft Company), hired an Airco DH.9 along with pilot entrepreneur Alan Cobham.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] From 1921, Aerofilms carried out vertical photography for survey and mapping purposes.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] During the 1930s, the company pioneered the science of photogrammetry (mapping from aerial photographs), with the Ordnance Survey amongst the company's clients.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] In 1920, the Australian Milton Kent started using a half-plate oblique aero camera purchased from Carl Zeiss AG in his aerial photographic business.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] Another successful pioneer of the commercial use of aerial photography was the American Sherman Fairchild who started with his own aircraft firm Fairchild Aircraft to develop and build specialized aircraft for high altitude aerial survey missions.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] One Fairchild aerial survey aircraft in 1935 carried a unit that combined two synchronized cameras.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] Utilizing two units of ten lenses each with a ten-inch lens, the aircraft took photos from 23,000 feet.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] Each photo covered two hundred and twenty-five square miles.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] One of its first government contracts was an aerial survey of New Mexico to study soil erosion.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] A year later, Fairchild introduced a better high altitude camera with a nine-lens in one unit that could take a photo covering 600 square miles with each exposure from 30,000 feet.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] In 1939, Sidney Cotton and Flying Officer Maurice Longbottom of the RAF were among the first to suggest that airborne reconnaissance may be a task better suited to fast, small aircraft which would use their speed and high service ceiling to avoid detection and interception.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] Although this seems obvious now, with modern reconnaissance tasks performed by fast, high flying aircraft, at the time it was radical thinking.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] They proposed the use of Spitfires with their armament and radios removed and replaced with extra fuel and cameras.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] This led to the development of the Spitfire PR variants.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] Spitfires proved to be extremely successful in their reconnaissance role and there were many variants built specifically for that purpose.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] They served initially with what later became No.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] 1 Photographic Reconnaissance Unit (PRU).
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] In 1928, the RAF developed an electric heating system for the aerial camera.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] This allowed reconnaissance aircraft to take pictures from very high altitudes without the camera parts freezing.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] Based at RAF Medmenham, the collection and interpretation of such photographs became a considerable enterprise.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] Cotton's aerial photographs were far ahead of their time.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] Together with other members of the 1 PRU, he pioneered the techniques of high-altitude, high-speed stereoscopic photography that were instrumental in revealing the locations of many crucial military and intelligence targets.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] Jones, photographs were used to establish the size and the characteristic launching mechanisms for both the V-1 flying bomb and the V-2 rocket.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] Cotton also worked on ideas such as a prototype specialist reconnaissance aircraft and further refinements of photographic equipment.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] At the peak, the British flew over 100 reconnaissance flights a day, yielding 50,000 images per day to interpret.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] Similar efforts were taken by other countries.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] While stationed on an aircraft carrier in Imperial Japan, FS Hussain, a pilot in the Royal Indian Air Force, was tasked with photographing the aftermath of the Atomic bombings of Hiroshima and Nagasaki.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] Unaware of the risks of exposure to radiation, it led to his death in 1969 at the age of 44.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] Vertical aerial photography is used in cartography (particularly in photogrammetric surveys, which are often the basis for topographic maps), land-use planning, aerial archaeology.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] Oblique aerial photography is used for movie production, environmental studies, power line inspection, surveillance, construction progress, commercial advertising, conveyancing, and artistic projects.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] An example of how aerial photography is used in the field of archaeology is the mapping project done at the site Angkor Borei in Cambodia from 1995 to 1996.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] Using aerial photography, archaeologists were able to identify archaeological features, including 112 water features (reservoirs, artificially constructed pools and natural ponds) within the walled site of Angkor Borei.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] In the United States, aerial photographs are used in many Phase I Environmental Site Assessments for property analysis.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] In the United States, except when necessary for take-off and landing, full-sized manned aircraft are prohibited from flying at altitudes under 1000 feet over congested areas and not closer than 500 feet from any person, vessel, vehicle or structure over non-congested areas.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] Certain exceptions are allowed for helicopters, powered parachutes and weight-shift-control aircraft.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] Advances in radio controlled models have made it possible for model aircraft to conduct low-altitude aerial photography.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] This had benefited real-estate advertising, where commercial and residential properties are the photographic subject.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] In 2014, the US Federal Aviation Administration banned the use of drones for photographs in real estate advertisements.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] The ban has been lifted and commercial aerial photography using drones of UAS is regulated under the FAA Reauthorization Act of 2018.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] Commercial pilots have to complete the requirements for a Part 107 license, while amateur and non-commercial use is restricted by the FAA.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] Small scale model aircraft offer increased photographic access to these previously restricted areas.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] Miniature vehicles do not replace full-size aircraft, as full-size aircraft are capable of longer flight times, higher altitudes, and greater equipment payloads.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] They are, however, useful in any situation in which a full-scale aircraft would be dangerous to operate.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] Examples would include the inspection of transformers atop power transmission lines and slow, low-level flight over agricultural fields, both of which can be accomplished by a large-scale radio-controlled helicopter.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] Professional-grade, gyroscopically stabilized camera platforms are available for use under such a model; a large model helicopter with a 26cc gasoline engine can hoist a payload of approximately seven kilograms (15 pounds).
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] One example is the radio controlled Nitrohawk helicopter developed by Robert Channon between 1988 and 1998.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] In addition to gyroscopically stabilized footage, the use of RC copters as reliable aerial photography tools increased with the integration of FPV (first-person-view) technology.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] Many radio-controlled aircraft, in particular drones, are now capable of utilizing Wi-Fi to stream live video from the aircraft's camera back to the pilot's or pilot in command's (PIC) ground station.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] In Australia, Civil Aviation Safety Regulation Part 101 (CASR Part 101) allows for commercial use of unmanned and remotely piloted aircraft.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] Under these regulations, unmanned remotely piloted aircraft for commercial are referred to as Remotely Piloted Aircraft Systems (RPAS), whereas radio-controlled aircraft for recreational purposes are referred to as model aircraft.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] Under CASR Part 101, businesses/persons operating remotely piloted aircraft commercially are required to hold an operator certificate, just like manned aircraft operators.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] Pilots of remotely piloted aircraft operating commercially are also required to be licensed by the Civil Aviation Safety Authority (CASA).
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] While a small RPAS and model aircraft may actually be identical, unlike model aircraft, a RPAS may enter controlled airspace with approval, and operate close to an aerodrome.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] Due to a number of illegal operators in Australia, making false claims of being approved, CASA maintains and publishes a list of approved remote operator's certificate (ReOC) holders.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] However, CASA has modified the regulations and from September 29, 2016, drones under 2 kg (4.4 lb) may be operated for commercial purposes.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] 2006 FAA regulations grounding all commercial RC model flights have been upgraded to require formal FAA certification before permission is granted to fly at any altitude in the US.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] On June 25, 2014, the FAA, in ruling 14 CFR Part 91 [Docket No.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] FAA–2014–0396] "Interpretation of the Special Rule for Model Aircraft", banned the commercial use of unmanned aircraft over U.S. airspace.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] On September 26, 2014, the FAA began granting the right to use drones in aerial filmmaking.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] Operators are required to be licensed pilots and must keep the drone in view at all times.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] Drones cannot be used to film in areas where people might be put at risk.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] The FAA Modernization and Reform Act of 2012 established, in Section 336, a special rule for model aircraft.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] In Section 336, Congress confirmed the FAA's long-standing position that model aircraft are aircraft.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] Because anything capable of being viewed from a public space is considered outside the realm of privacy in the United States, aerial photography may legally document features and occurrences on private property.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] The FAA can pursue enforcement action against persons operating model aircraft who endanger the safety of the national airspace system: Public Law 112–95, section 336(b).
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] On June 21, 2016, the FAA released its summary of small unmanned aircraft rules (Part 107).
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] The rules established guidelines for small UAS operators including operating only during the daytime, a 400 ft (120 m). ceiling and pilots must keep the UAS in visual range.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] On April 7, 2017, the FAA announced special security instructions under 14 CFR § 99.7.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] Effective April 14, 2017, all UAS flights within 400 feet of the lateral boundaries of U.S. military installations are prohibited unless a special permit is secured from the base and/or the FAA.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] Aerial photography in the UK has tight regulations as to where a drone is able to fly.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] Aerial Photography on Light aircraft under 20 kg (44 lb).
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] Basic Rules for non commercial flying Of a SUA (Small Unmanned Aircraft).
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] Article 241 Endangering safety of any person or property states that a person must not recklessly or negligently cause or permit an aircraft to endanger any person or property.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] The person in charge of a small unmanned aircraft may only fly the aircraft if reasonably satisfied that the flight can safely be made.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] The person in charge of a small unmanned aircraft must maintain direct, unaided visual contact with the aircraft sufficient to monitor its flight path in relation to other aircraft, persons, vehicles, vessels and structures for the purpose of avoiding collisions.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] The person in charge of a small unmanned aircraft must not fly the aircraft for the purposes of commercial operations except in accordance with a permission granted by the CAA.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] Over or within 150 m (490 ft) of an organised open-air assembly of more than 1,000 persons.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] Within 50 m (160 ft) of any vessel, vehicle or structure which is not under the control of the person in charge of the aircraft.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] Within 50 m of any person, during take-off or landing, a small unmanned surveillance aircraft must not be flown within 30 m (98 ft) of any person.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] This does not apply to the person in charge of the small unmanned surveillance aircraft or a person under the control of the person in charge of the aircraft.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] Model aircraft with a mass of more than 20 kg are termed 'Large Model Aircraft' – within the UK, large model aircraft may only be flown in accordance with an exemption from the ANO, which must be issued by the CAA.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] Photographs taken at an angle are called *oblique photographs*.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] If they are taken from a low angle relative to the earth's surface, they are called *low oblique* and photographs taken from a high angle are called *high* or *steep oblique*.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] Vertical photographs are taken straight down.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] They are mainly used in photogrammetry and image interpretation.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] Pictures that will be used in photogrammetry are traditionally taken with special large format cameras with calibrated and documented geometric properties.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] Depending on their purpose, it can be done in several ways, of which a few are listed below.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] Vertical photographs are often used to create orthophotos, alternatively known as orthophotomaps, photographs which have been geometrically "corrected" so as to be usable as a map.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] In other words, an orthophoto is a simulation of a photograph taken from an infinite distance, looking straight down to nadir.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] Perspective must obviously be removed, but variations in terrain should also be corrected for.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] Multiple geometric transformations are applied to the image, depending on the perspective and terrain corrections required on a particular part of the image.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] Orthophotos are commonly used in geographic information systems, such as are used by mapping agencies (e.g.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] Once the images have been aligned, or "registered", with known real-world coordinates, they can be widely deployed.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] Large sets of orthophotos, typically derived from multiple sources and divided into "tiles" (each typically 256 x 256 pixels in size), are widely used in online map systems such as Google Maps.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] OpenStreetMap offers the use of similar orthophotos for deriving new map data.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] Google Earth overlays orthophotos or satellite imagery onto a digital elevation model to simulate 3D landscapes.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] Aerial photography may be labeled as either "leaf-off" or on "leaf-on" to indicate whether deciduous foliage is in the photograph.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] Leaf-off photographs show less foliage or no foliage at all, and are used to see the ground and things on the ground more closely.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] Leaf-on photographs are used to measure crop health and yield.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] For forestry purposes, some species of trees are easier to distinguish from other kinds of trees with leaf-off photography, while other species are easier to distinguish with leaf-on photography.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] With advancements in video technology, aerial video is becoming more popular.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] Orthogonal video is shot from aircraft mapping pipelines, crop fields, and other points of interest.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] Using GPS, video may be embedded with meta data and later synced with a video mapping program.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] This "Spatial Multimedia" is the timely union of digital media including still photography, motion video, stereo, panoramic imagery sets, immersive media constructs, audio, and other data with location and date-time information from the GPS and other location designs.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] Aerial videos are emerging Spatial Multimedia which can be used for scene understanding and object tracking.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] The input video is captured by low flying aerial platforms and typically consists of strong parallax from non-ground-plane structures.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] The integration of digital video, global positioning systems (GPS) and automated image processing will improve the accuracy and cost-effectiveness of data collection and reduction.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] Several different aerial platforms are under investigation for the data collection.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] In film production, it is common to use a unmanned aerial vehicle with a mounted cine camera.
[src:alesia-city/aerial-photography] For example, the AERIGON cinema drone is used for low aerial shots in big blockbuster movies.
[src:alesia-city/agesinates] The **Agesinates** or **Cambolectri Agessinates** were an ancient Celtic tribe living in Gallia Aquitania during the Roman period.
[src:alesia-city/agesinates] They are mentioned as *Cambolectri Agessinates* by Pliny (1st c.
[src:alesia-city/agesinates] The ethnic name *Cambolectri* derives from the Gaulish stem *cambo*- ('curve, meander').
[src:alesia-city/agesinates] The second element -*lectri* is also attested in a Celtic personal name (*Lictoria*, *Lectri*).
[src:alesia-city/agesinates] Pliny also refers to another group of Cambolectri that was "surnamed Atlantici" (*Cambolectri qui Atlantici cognominantur*), which he locates in Gallia Narbonensis.
[src:alesia-city/agesinates] It is unclear whether this designation refers to another faction of the same people, implying a division between the two provinces, or to a distinct people altogether.
[src:alesia-city/agesinates] Michel Molin has suggested that this double mention may reflect a border *civitas* that either belonged alternately to eatch province, or was divided between them, as was the case with the Ruteni.
[src:alesia-city/agesinates] Pliny places them in Gallia Aquitania, alongside the Vasates (*Vassei*) and Sennates.
[src:alesia-city/agesinates] Paul-Marie Duval proposed situating the territory of the Cambolectri Agessinates on the lower or middle Garonne river.
[src:alesia-city/agesinates] Duval maintains that placing the Agessinates near the Pictones, with Aizenai (Bas-Poitou) as their chief town, as proposed by Alfred Holder, would require an implausible syntactic linkage in Pliny's text.
[src:alesia-city/agesinates] He further notes that the suffix *-ates*, which is particularly frequent in Aquitania compared to the rest of Gaul, more more plausibly supports this location than an attribution north of the Garonne.
[src:alesia-city/alesia-city] The country of Keltikē was ruled by a renowned king whose daughter was unusually tall and was more beautiful than all other maidens, due to which she considered every man who asked her hand in marriage as unworthy of her and rejected them.
[src:alesia-city/alesia-city] ", visited Keltikē and founded the city of Alesia there.
[src:alesia-city/alesia-city] The king's daughter was impressed by his physical excellence and had a son with him named Galatēs, who was more righteous and powerful than all the youths of his tribe.
[src:alesia-city/alesia-city] When Galatēs had reached adulthood, he became king and a great warrior, and he conquered much of the areas surrounding his tribe's territory.
[src:alesia-city/alesia-city] Alesia is best known for being the site of the decisive Battle of Alesia in 52 BC that marked the defeat of the Gauls under Vercingetorix by the Romans under Julius Caesar.
[src:alesia-city/alesia-city] Caesar described the battle in detail in his *Commentarii de Bello Gallico* (Book VII, 69–90).
[src:alesia-city/alesia-city] The battle's outcome determined the fate of all of Gaul: in winning the battle, the Romans won both the Gallic Wars and dominion over Gaul.
[src:alesia-city/alesia-city] After being conquered by Caesar, Alesia became a Gallo-Roman town.
[src:alesia-city/alesia-city] It featured a town centre with monumental buildings such as temples and a forum.
[src:alesia-city/alesia-city] For a long time after the abandonment of the Roman town, the location of Alesia and thus the site of the important battle was unknown and subject to speculation.
[src:alesia-city/alesia-city] In the 19th century, Emperor Napoleon III developed an interest in the location of this crucial battle in pre-French history.
[src:alesia-city/alesia-city] He was writing a biography of Caesar and saw the command of Vercingetorix over all Gaulish armies as a symbol of the French nation.
[src:alesia-city/alesia-city] At the same time he realized that the future French nation was heavily influenced by the Roman victory and centuries of rule over Gaul.
[src:alesia-city/alesia-city] In 1838 an inscription *IN ALISIIA* was discovered near Alise-Sainte-Reine in the department Côte-d'Or near Dijon.
[src:alesia-city/alesia-city] Napoleon III ordered an archaeological excavation by Eugène Stoffel around Mont-Auxois.
[src:alesia-city/alesia-city] These excavations from 1861 to 1865 concentrated on the vast Roman siege lines and indicated that the historical Alesia was indeed located there.
[src:alesia-city/alesia-city] The *oppidum* was located on a plateau of c.
[src:alesia-city/alesia-city] 97 hectares (240 acres), around 200 metres (660 ft) above the valley floor, surrounded by steep cliffs in every direction except at the eastern and western extremities.
[src:alesia-city/alesia-city] Later archaeological analysis at Alise-Sainte-Reine has corroborated the described siege in detail.
[src:alesia-city/alesia-city] The remains of siege rings said to match Caesar's descriptions have been identified by archaeologists using aerial photography (e.g. by René Goguey).
[src:alesia-city/alesia-city] Franco-German excavations led by Michel Reddé and Siegmar von Schnurbein from 1991–97 confirmed these findings and effectively ended the long debate among archaeologists about the location of Alesia.
[src:alesia-city/alesia-city] There have been other theories about Alesia's location that claimed it was in Franche-Comté or around Salins-les-Bains in Jura.
[src:alesia-city/alesia-city] In the 1960s, a French archaeologist, André Berthier, proposed that the location of Alesia is at Chaux-des-Crotenay in Franche-Comté, at the gate of the Jura mountains—a place that according to him better suits the descriptions in Caesar's Gallic Wars.
[src:alesia-city/alesia-city] This theory is not supported by archaeological or historical research.
[src:alesia-city/alesia-city] In total, around 40 towns and other locations have claimed to be the site of Alesia.
[src:alesia-city/alesia-city] Part of the area has become the MuséoParc Alésia.
[src:alesia-city/alesia-city] Not much of the Gallic *oppidum* is visible today, except for some remains of a rampart.
[src:alesia-city/alesia-city] Most of the ruins date to the town's Roman period.
[src:alesia-city/alesia-city] A large copper statue of Vercingetorix, made in 1865 by Aimé Millet, stands at the western end of the plateau.
[src:alesia-city/alesia-city] The uncertainty surrounding Alesia's location is humorously parodied in the Asterix comic book *Asterix and the Chieftain's Shield*, in which, in this case because of Gaulish pride, characters repeatedly and vehemently deny that they know its location: "I don't know where Alesia is!
